No liberating amendment for Tymoshenko by Parliament
Today, the Ukrainian parliament refused the request to abolish those clauses on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko had been convicted in the context of a amendment to the Criminal Code.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the liberation of the imprisoned expremier minister, was rejected by the MEPs at the second reading of the request to mitigate the penalties for economic offences.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for concluding an allegedly detrimental contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, in December the appeal of the convicted persons is to be negotiated in court.
Timoshenko himself described the sentence as a political revenge of the regime and in the West, too, the trial raised suspicions of the prejudice of the court.
The request to remove Section 365 from the Criminal Code, on the basis of which the Expremier Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 Members of Parliament.
226 votes would have been necessary for its adoption.
