Iranian students are ready to die for their country's core program.
They formed a living shield.
Several hundred university students formed a living shield around a core object in Iran.
With this gesture, they wanted to demonstrate their support for their country's core program before a possible Israeli attack.
The students had prayed in front of the object at noon on Tuesday and then proclaimed death to the US and Israel.
A few hundred students from the university in Isfahan, Iran, made a living sign around the nuclear technology center in Isfahan on Tuesday, where uranium is processed.
They wanted to make it clear that they were willing to protect their country's core program, if necessary, with their own lives.
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) recently stated in its report that Iran seems to have long since given up its efforts to build a nuclear weapon.
Israel is also talking about a possible attack on Iranian nuclear facilities.
Students had prayed at noon before the entrance to the complex and then proclaimed death to the US and Israel.
According to the Israeli press, if the Iranian nuclear program was to be largely paralysed, the nuclear enrichment plant at Natan's target would also be from the center in Isfahan.
A fat child's menu: It doesn't eat breakfast and eats sausage for supper
More than a third of children from 9 to 13 have problems with overweight, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that obese children usually come from unhealthy families.
This shows once again how important the milieu in which he grows up is for the healthy development of a human being and the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half more often on the table than in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of overweight children had fries for dinner on the day before the reconnaissance under the motto "Adipositas is no coincidence."
In families with fat people, sports are not exactly one of the favourite activities, but also the majority of today's students - only 15 percent answered that their parents find themselves at least once a week for active exercise.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place last year towards the end of the school year, with nearly 900 children from primary schools in the whole of the Czech Republic being interviewed.
This was already the second year of the action "Adipositas is not a coincidence," which is supported by the General Health Insurance Fund and the Unilever Society.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th grades participated in the project.
Unhealthy food and lack of exercise in the family are decisive factors that are responsible for the alarmingly increasing number of children with overweight or even obesity.
"For example, only half of the children surveyed indicated eating breakfast-second breakfast-lunch-vesper-evening bread five times a day - one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet," says one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for supper
Experts point out that relatively small things, such as the regular breakfast time of the family, are also important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the pupils' families have breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
The worst thing was the fact that every tenth family did not have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
Among other things, the survey test showed that families of overweight children consume unhealthy fries much more often.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet sodas every day (70 percent)
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed exercise, less than half of their parents do so - only 15 percent.
Match your own menu
Another part of the survey enabled selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to compile their own menu from the opportunities offered for appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among their favorite dishes were many pastries, meat dishes and, of course, desserts.
"Alarming is above all the great popularity of sweet sodas," is emphasized in the final report to this survey.
At lunch, i.e. the main dish, pasta won just in front of poultry.
Legumes almost didn't like the children at all and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was also very low.
Returning to Health
At the same time, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits when they get the right information.
"In many cases, the control group of the survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the enlightening presentation "Adiposity is not a coincidence" showed a significant shift in preferences towards principles of healthy nutrition," the results of the project point out.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet limos, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
In the questionnaire, the children also used poultry or fish much more often as the main dish of the day and were willing to eat less dumplings or sweet food.
Professionals claim - a stylist must also be a good psychologist
