So you really have to be clever.
Mario delighted me by praising my "creation" without restrictions.
The skill mentioned is not exactly my strength.
All of this was only a fraction of what we heard on the second weekend's continuation course.
One thing has become clear to me in the meantime - devoting oneself to styling at a professional level is not child's play.
V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The originally carefree ride is made by a series of completely avoidable, dilettant mistakes to the routine journey to the early shift.
Although it was possible to fulfill the ambitions to a large extent, what good is that when obviously no one wanted to do a little more.
Even before he came to the counters, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
After all, he promised to move the long-standing game series "Need for Speed" back into a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples he didn't seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about how the adapted passages fail, in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you are already used to at NFS, in the end a lot is different than you expected.
Sure - potentially they are quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is reduced by some unnecessary mistakes that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So they are actually no longer mistakes, but rather signs of a basically incomprehensible laziness of game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
For the first time, one is introduced into history, whose main character Jack has certain problems of personal character; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, i.e. on the west coast, you get on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea includes a whole series of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different track and that the individual stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don't have the impression that game would offer the same thing over and over again.
Some environments are also very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphic does not go beyond that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing moving around the world.
But the journey through the desert, through autumnal landscape or high up through deep snowy landscape looks visually very pleasant.
Occasionally, atypical elements bring a little variety into the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm that severely restricts the view.
In the mountains, in turn, you have to be hellishly careful not to get spilled by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are installed quite well in a row.
Only a few, but they're enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stopwatch), then you still expect a personal duel with a single competitor.
And that's what the police are trying to do. They're trying to screw up the whole thing.
A novelty is passages in which Jack leaves the car.
It's more about certain interactive animations in which Jack flees from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are much fewer such passages in the game than one would expect (in concrete terms only three).
Ultimately, this is more for the benefit of the game, because at least this element has no chance of getting bored - it belongs in the context of the above mentioned one of the elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model moves in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, from today's point of view, it does not tear out trees, on the other hand, it could not be said that it would be bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you have to look elsewhere.
But the local driving model will continue to do well for action-packed racing, although you could find better in the competition.
Until then, everything will be fine.
Real problems only appear after some time.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not quite O.K.
From a game of this kind, it is hardly to be expected that it will calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea how the car behaves before any impact on any object, then obviously everything is not okay.
Typical example: When passing or passing close cars, one "trips" the other car only easily in some places, but in other, almost identical situations one gets into the sling and spins wild pirouettes.
Or you're gonna take the car to shit.
Thanks to the Restart system, it doesn't matter anymore, but it's annoying.
The restarts are solved like this: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, then the game throws you back to the last clue of the track.
Only - in each race you only have five restarts.
Once you've exhausted it, everything starts over...
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something doesn't succeed, but you shouldn't rely on it.
Sometimes, however, not even the residual type helps, nothing but to learn the critical section from the head.
It is very unpleasant that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, you have to go through some curves in a very specific way, otherwise you simply don't fit through.
Elsewhere you always encounter "civil" cars in the same configuration, whether you are the first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is particularly annoying in situations when you see that the opponent passes by two cars in front of a game, but until you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive them around or brake them.
And it doesn't matter when you get there, because everything is designed in such a way that this situation always comes close to your nose.
The competitors have further advantages.
In the whole game there are a few places where you will always be overtaken by the same opponent in the same place and again without regard to the time.
Most crazy is to finish the game on the long bridge that you pass in the opposite direction.
The opponent's got to make up for one of these guys, obviously, coming out of here on the devil.
And if he's in front of you, then of course he takes the view, so that you start driving your own car a few times in Klump.
Of course - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly prevents you from enjoying the game.
And that's a pity, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining and sometimes so loaded with action that you almost no longer know where your head is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what is "guilt" about it - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boredom can arise, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the change of cars during the races.
One must not overlook the petrol stations along the route, because it is precisely here that one can change the car, although in most cases the car that one has just had is sufficient.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American saloons for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for the technical trips, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
The task mode (Challenges) also goes hand in hand with the mode of game history - that is, the races in the individual locations you know from history.
Here, there are not only medals, but also points of experience for your own profile, which is common to the tasks (challenges) and the history.
In order to get to the higher level of the driver, different items have to be opened up: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is also connected to the online function Autolog, which compares, among other things, the own results achieved with those of other players and also provides for further collective functions.
One of the other incomprehensible carvers is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you get by car into a subway tunnel (meinetwegen), where you rest in the dark on the rails long (meinetwegen).
On the speedometer there are numbers between 150 a 200 km/h (meinewegen), but suddenly a subway comes from behind and goes uncompromisingly to scrap.
In our editorial office, we will argue for a long time whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think us to be so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases quite appealing and even brilliant here and there.
It is all the more annoying that with some exciting moments the refresh rate is slowing down and sometimes quite dramatic.
However, this applies particularly to accidents involving a larger number of participants, where continuous FPS is of no use anyway.
The soundtrack is as far as OK and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to address a scale as wide as possible rather young audiences, a soundtrack a lá was created "of everyone something" - but who buys such a game already because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are rather mixed.
If the game weren't reduced by the above-mentioned totally unnecessary mistakes, we could have said with the chest tone of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that's how the game seems unfinished.
In itself a great pleasure, but you should be prepared for these mistakes with the power of airport headlights in your eyes.
Concert of the "Students of the Velvet Revolution" with singing ensembles of the Charles University
The Festival Festa Academica offers for the third time the combination of the World Student Day with the anniversary of the Samtenen Revolution and this including music experience.
During the festival, the twenty specialist and university choirs will be introduced.
The focus of the festival is on the two concerts, which take place on November 17th.
"The Karlsuniversität has a large share in the festival."
"Among the participants is also the choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanistic Studies, and the Festival Committee also includes the Rector Václav Hampl," said Jakub Čaloun, head of the organization team.
The absolute highlight of the festival is the public concert of specialist school choirs, which takes place on November 17th from 2 pm on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The programme includes the composition of the important Czech jazz musician Karel Růžička "Celebration Jazz Mass."
In the evening hours the concert "Students of the Velvet Revolution" (Studenty Sametu) takes place in the gala rooms of the Volkshaus in Vinohrady, where also university choirs perform, choirs of the Charles University are not excluded.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate the World Students' Day worthy and to commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Samten Revolution, but to present choir music to the public at the highest level and to promote the creative cooperation of young people.
The main organizer is the Association of Czech Choirs in cooperation with the Johannes-Kepler-Gymnasium.
The event was sponsored by Bohuslav Svoboda, Mayor of Prague and Václav Hampl, Rector of Charles University.
The festival takes place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
Besides concerts, the schedule also includes numerous music meetings, student happanings, matinees and other events.
Detailed information can be found on the website of the festival www.festaacademica.cz
