The innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence
If one wanted to look for a suitable word that characterizes IBM's strategy most accurately, then this would probably be the word "longevity."
For the general public, IBM is the synonym for technological revolution, it is known as a modern company, although it has passed a century since it was founded.
The basis for this longevity was already laid by her first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson sen.
He already spoke of the slogan that countless worldwide problems could easily be solved if people were willing to think a little.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the hallmark for the life of the future giant (and at the same time the title of the company's internal magazine, which was published by IBM in 1935).
This was also the basis of the company culture thoroughly prepared by Watsen.
"For us from IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and was also successful for a whole century because it remained true to its principles and did not shy away from changing everything else all around.
This allowed us to transform technologies, business and society in the course of our first century.
We hope that we will achieve even more in the next hundred years," said Samuel J. Palmisano, today's director of the company on the occasion of the anniversary.
Thought-out system
Watson already had social care for his employees in the thirties - in a similar way to the entrepreneur Baťa in Czechoslovakia: The IBM people had as one of the first American employees paid vacation, an insurance by the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as workwear and a thoughtful pay system for best newers and traders.
The long-term relationships between IBM and its customers are equally sophisticated.
From the very beginning, the company was ingenious in talent promotion - as one of the first companies in the world, IBM lifted all discrimination - and was able to choose accordingly.
In line with this anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan that Palmisan will be replaced by a woman at the head of IBM next year - by Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for thirty years, so far she has taken up the position of head of sales, marketing and strategy.
In recent years, IBM has been making so-called online brainstormings, from which many future strategies and innovations grow.
No wonder - there are enough ideas, in the company almost half a million people are busy.
An institution with a good reputation
Their unshakable position in the business guarantees the company a strong image, both internally and externally.
"From the beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than a mere technology company," Economist said the professor of Harvard Business School and the author of a book about IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
"IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems with technology," added George Colony of Consulting-Company Forrester Research.
As the company itself points out, it is a difference to be only present in the market or to form it directly through this presence.
IBM - called "Big Blue" in the states of its logo because of its family, has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a century.
It is one of the most versatile technology companies in the world - IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructures, hosting and consultation services in an incredible product range - from servers to nanotechnology.
Of all American technology companies, IBM owns the most patents and already five of its employees were awarded the Nobel Prize.
Among his most famous inventions are e.g. ATMs, credit cards, financial swap, barcode or also the floppy disk.
With approximately $220 billion of stock market value (market capitalization), IBM was the second-largest technology company this year (just after Apple), with Microsoft overtaking it for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all products and innovations met the tastes of today's customers - unhappy were, for example, the attempt with the OS/2 operating system, the online service Prodigy or the computers IBM PC jr.
"Business is based on the forward movement, so you must not be emotionally committed to the past," says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That's why IBM has no problem building its foundations on different platforms - and if they don't work, leaving them again.
Unlike the opponent Microsoft, which basically stands and falls with its operating system Windows.
Promising Technologies
One fifth of IBM's profits are attributable to services, software and hardware.
In 1990, hardware with a share of more than fifty percent was the most represented.
Since 2000, IBM has sold little profit-giving assets worth $15 billion, but at the same time it invested $58 billion in purchasing promising technologies.
In these investments, IBM continues after 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world like a storm for the first time.
Here, too, IBM remained faithful to the legacy of its first boss Thomas J. Watson, who increased his investment volume in the middle of the Great Depression.
So far, it seems that IBM will survive today's crisis without prejudice.
The value of IBM shares has increased by 120 percent rocket-like since 2008 and the company's net profit is growing continuously.
IBM's corporate slogan is: everything can be changed - only the values can't be changed.
This is also why it can be expected that this flexible giant will also master the next crisis.
IBM history: From cheese cutters to spaceflights
Founded 100 years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was taken over only in 1924 - originally a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for the later IBM company was the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They had technologies such as the famous flashcard clocks for registering the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint, who was also chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930, became the architect of this new company.
And it was Flint who hired Thomas J. Watson, head of the competition, to help him manage the company.
This leader then even put the founders of IBM in the shade - on Watson's ideas the invincible culture and identity of the company is still based today.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the production and distribution of all possible machines for the trade - from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
In the first four decades when Watson ran the company, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable for the company that he sat in the boss's chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960 ' s, IBM technicians and computers helped NASA flight into space - to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969 also to the famous flight of man to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which defined the computer standard of that time, came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consulting part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business with consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has paid off in the last three years is the concept of "Smart Planet."
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas that have not even been planned so far, e.g. to improve the situation in transport and urban administration.
In the retail sector, IBM recently launched the Smarter Commerce platform to help retailers manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
Already in 1932, IBM founded a branch in the former Czechoslovakia - as the first country ever in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and there is also a world-class top research team that deals with voice recognition technology.
