Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five approved state travel agencies: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, the travel agencies sold only travels to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, and only the chosen ones were allowed to travel to the West.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), the Soviet Union (Sochi on the peninsula of Crimea on the Black Sea), Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and Hungary to the Balaton.
One notable exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore the travels to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern bloc (also Czechoslovakia) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of socialist countries.
For example, if a ČSSR citizen wanted to travel individually to Poland or even the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then you had to accept huge snakes or also stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, things hadn't worked out by a long time.
The so-called foreign currency announcement - the condition for an exit to the West - was granted only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
In fact, the Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without foreign currency announcement it would have been impossible to find the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays in Germany, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dachshunds - a habit that continues to this day.
The velvet revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs on its feet.
While a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which one is no longer aware of today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czechs - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the nineties of the last century, foreign exchange obligations to neighbouring Western European countries were abolished, resulting in a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
Thus, the Czech holidaymakers slept in the park while traveling to Paris, because who would have had the money to stay in the hotel or in a guesthouse at that time.
A typical feature of Czech foreign travel was a trunk packed with canned beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech krona - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and thus the average salaries increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began to prepare regular trips through charter flights after 1997, making it incredibly cheaper for air travel than in the past, thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the USA, already had non-devisory payments with all highly developed countries in the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-velvet" travel came in 2000 when, thanks to high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was handled - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft fly annually with Czech passengers to far-away sunny countries; this year you fly directly from the Czech Republic twelve exotic destinations.
Every year, 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history spent more than 15 thousand CZK per capita for a single holiday stay, including the costs at the resort.
The general meeting is to find a new chairman - again a stalemate threatens.
For almost five months, Czech football has no chairman, and it threatens that the successor of Ivan Hašek at the head of the Czech Football Association (FAČR) will not even be known after the extraordinary general meeting on Thursday in Nymburk.
To date, there is no agreement as to the electoral order to be chosen.
And without these, no vote on the three potential successors is possible at all.
Three interested parties want to manage Czech football - Jindřich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Paclík.
In June, Hašek resigned from his post, urging his colleagues to come to an agreement and find a strong personality who could lead football in the future.
Only - in the era after Hašek the old tangles broke out again between the two federation chambers, which cannot agree on a common candidate.
This was obvious on 16 September when the new Chairman was to be elected.
The delegates of the Annual General Meeting had come to the People's House in the Smíchov district of Prague for nothing, because the negotiations did not result in any result and it was not just about the election itself.
One could not even agree on who is actually entitled to vote in the full collection - only the statutory representatives or also the officials with a power of attorney.
On this only point, at least partial agreement was reached, and the recommendation of the Institute for State and Law contributed to this, whose opinion was that representation on a proxy basis was not valid.
However, disputes over the electoral order continue.
Nor did the Executive Committee bring any more clarity to the matter, at which meetings, whether ordinary or extraordinary, are in principle no longer on the agenda at all.
Even though the views on the election changed a few times - the neuralgic point remained the same.
The question is: how to proceed in the 3rd round in order to avoid a stalemate situation?
"The point of contention concerns the question of whether to proceed in accordance with the statutes or whether a completely different model needs to be found," said Dušan Svoboda, one of the three vice-presidents of the FAČR, who represents professional football in management.
According to the statutory model, in the third round, the candidate who receives the larger percentage support in the chamber for which he is running wins.
Moravia is supposedly willing to respond to the compromise that the candidate who receives the higher number of votes from both chambers wins.
The Czech side, on the other hand, insists on the condition that the winner receives at least a two-thirds majority in this percentage vote counting.
"Then the two preliminary rounds have no meaning at all, this mode would question the entire two-chamber concept," Svoboda understands the objections of the Moravian side, which it would be best not to turn the electoral order but to choose according to the valid statutes.
Surprisingly, Tomáš Paclík agrees, even if it turns out that the statutory electoral order of all candidates is most likely to meet Pelta.
"My wish is that most of the time be elected according to the statutes."
"So that no absurd alternative variants can be devised, as at the last Annual General Meeting," said the owner (of the football club) Victoria Plzeň, who for the first time ran for the first time and in his comments was mainly against Pelta.
But Pelta remains optimistic.
In his opinion, the new chairman will be known in Nymburk and he believes that the candidates will also work together constructively in the future.
"The potential qualification of the national team for the football championship today would certainly contribute to calming the minds."
"If football first rides the euphoric wave, then the willingness to cooperate is also greater," says the official from Jablonec, who has the greatest experience of all three adepts, both professional and regional.
Rajchl is more reserved.
"I hope to reach an agreement, but unfortunately the situation is ambiguous."
"This is not a matter between the people of Bohemia and Moravia, but there are certain efforts to "bend" the regulations for their own purposes.
"Therefore, a new blocking at the Annual General Meeting is not excluded."
"I hope, however, that common sense ultimately wins," Rajchl said.
Only - a lot of time to agree on all sides is not left.
Some negotiations should allegedly take place directly in Montenegro, but who knows if the generality of football will be complete until the qualifying match.
The charter aircraft, with which, among other things, Dalibor Kučera and Rajchl were to fly to Podgorice, could not take off in Prague in the morning due to a technical disturbance and so they feverishly searched for a replacement variant, how to bring a part of the executive committee still to the venue of the Barrage play.
In the end, the ministerial meeting, which is supposed to be held on Wednesday, is crucial.
Josef Dobeš, Minister of Education, Youth and Physical Education, would have liked to have persuaded the split parties within the country's largest sports association to reach an agreement.
There is a lot at stake: state grants, the trustworthiness of Czech football and also the upcoming general meeting of the ČSTV, which is supposed to lead the Czech sport in the new direction after the financial problems of Sazka.
Paclík goes into the fight for the position of the chairman because he does not see a suitable candidate
If Tomáš Paclík, the head of the Pilsner footballers, could have made up a strong candidate before the Extraordinary General Meeting, who would have fulfilled all his ideas about the new chairman of the Football Association of the Czech Republic (FAČR), he would not have been involved in the fight for this top position at all.
