Europe's Most Beautiful Pools
Jump into the blue
By Julia Stanek
Paddling pool in Ufo-Optics, magnificent pools in Budapest: If you travel through Europe, you can experience your blue miracle - and after a city tour or a hike rest your tired legs in spa.
A book shows where wellness in the water is most beautiful.
If Iris Meder went on a research trip for the past one and a half years, one could not be missing in her luggage: her bathing suit.
Lying back on the water, she looked up in artfully designed domes, she swam towards marble putts waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and marveled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming pools.
If she liked a bath, she took it in her notebook - along with some interesting details about the construction and history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools explored architecture historian Meder in this way - and now presents her in her recently published book "Badenfreuden": Volksschwimmhallen in Munich, historical bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "Hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
Through 13 countries she led her "journey to the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe": In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and each city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
She doesn't have much to do with sports, says Meder - only in the water that's different.
It's annoying that swimming fans have to deal with blue tiles and chlorine stench, while joggers can breathe in the beguiling scent of spruce forests or listen to cheerful bird chirping in the park.
"I wondered one day why swimming pools must always be so ugly," says the Meders living in Vienna.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
Plattering in the diving pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in baths is so great because all senses are served, according to Meder.
And when the builders have made an effort, swimming pools can be a real feast for the eyes: "Instead of a floor one has a water surface in baths."
"It is transparent on the one hand, but reflects the beauty of the whole building."
Everything doubles visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, springboards.
The small-format picture book "Badefreuden" conveys on 190 pages interesting facts about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases - but above all makes you want to jump into the blue.
The pool collector Meder discovered remarkable specimens during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi bath in Budapest, she found a nitrate-containing water in a rustic karst cave (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) as well as a thermal bath whose basins are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
Spectacular views, on the other hand, offer many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria: While one has the whole city in mind from the Zurich roof bath, one can look at the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton - and: In the steam bath there is a window from which one can observe the hustle and bustle on the ski slope.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits bath guests in Längenfeld: The Aquadome Ötztal looks like a Ufo just landed in the Alps.
It vaporizes from three open bowls in winter, while in the background the mountains of the Ötztal rise to the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool the pool collector Meder rose the smell of chlorine in the nose.
Many thermal baths smell like sulphur, in the Árpád bath in the Hungarian Békescsaba it stinks so much like fuel oil, which one hardly believes to have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkali-hydrogen carbonate-containing medicinal water, which is almost black and whose slick sticks to the skin as soon as you slide into the pelvis - a wellness experience of a special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing spots: when she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing pool in the Czech bath Luhatschowitz, she found a closed terrain.
The bathroom, designed by architect Dušan Jurkovic in 1902, has now been closed.
When Meder looked through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing between the tiles.
On the other hand, one has counteracted the decay in an enchanting swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
Three phases of construction have already been completed by this bathroom; not only are neo-Romanesque elements from the time it was built in 1844, but also a Moorish Alhambra-style hall, which was added around 1900.
Since the careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favourite swimming pool of pool connoisseur Iris Meder - and not only because it originally comes from the Black Forest.
"It is already an achievement to merge so different architectural styles into such a great unit," says Meder.
With such a palace, the dive in the thermal pool is obviously only a minor matter.
