He made the architect so well known that he also built the pavilion at the next World Exhibition of Austria.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like annex in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
After the World Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at Vienna's Südbahnhof, his pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, had been rebuilt and opened in 1962 a museum of the 20th century - the "20er Haus" was called it.
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art got a new house in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building stood empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used as a museum for contemporary art in the future.
Tuesday evening the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a stroke of luck in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Galerie Belvedere in 2007, has completed the new start.
Husslein-Arco, a doctorate in art historian with a remarkable career, among other things in youth as a figure skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, strongly implemented the conversion with politicians and conservationists, raised public funds and private sponsorship money and determined the use.
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there was to be a café and a bookstore, and an office building had to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
Krischanitz was then the ideal occupation for the realization.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied with Schicker at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was for him an "unbelievably important place" where he had "almost every weekend" looked at the exhibitions.
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost in his transfer to Vienna and his re-use of generosity and ease.
There were far bigger problems with the current conversion: The building was "an energy hurler," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass façade were replaced, glass fibre reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof replaced by special safety glass.
Cold-bridge steel beams have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been refurbished.
Two basements brought space for the new use, a lowered light ditch between house and street provides for the exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light cock pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old reddish brown rust protection shade.
And the cinema is still exactly as it used to be.
And all this under strict supervision of the Monument Authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also liked the monument conservation office," says Krischanitz and points to a rough ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and modifications, the building has remained flexible and light.
It had been difficult with the pavilion "which came from Brussels," Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story."
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken a real consciousness."
In this case, however, the 21er Haus is not in the wrong place, because an urbanistic stroke of luck has occurred: Around the Swiss garden, the completely new planned "Hauptbahnhofsquartier" is being created, with office and residential buildings.
