The politicians approved up to 68 billion Swiss francs or about 45 billion euros in order to save the large bank before bankruptcy.
How could that happen?
Speaking to Swiss bankers, they see the problem above all in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three major Swiss banks joined forces to form a huge group.
A bank was created, which was already too big for small Switzerland during the merger - and grew ever further.
The two different predecessor banks of UBS were complementary: a rich but sleepy bank with a focus on asset management in Zurich and a poorer, but already more internationalized bank.
Suddenly, the internationalized investment bankers got a lot of money, with which they could turn a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, Chief Executive Officer of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
