How to Discover a Lie
A look at the current headlines shows how serious and widespread deception and lie are in everyday life.
The Republican presidential candidate, Herman Cain, is concerned with the allegations of sexual harassment on the part of several women. Both sides are lying to each other.
The management of Penn State is accused of perjury, as reports have allegedly been withheld that a retired football coach has sexually abused boys.
Last week, an open microphone was heard when French President Nikolas Sarkozy told President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
The New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself when he circulated denials that were quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of violations in campaign funding associated with cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who's seen it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered when he lied about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in the Oval Office.
Stories about cheating in school and college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents in which teachers have given their students the exam answers so that they could stand well even during their performance checks.
Mentors, who should teach the opposite, send a message that lies and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
Many of these lies, however, are considered to be emergency lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
To recognize lies or "discover lies" is one that is important for every person to learn, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game such as Sharades, where it is the goal to call "Have yourself!" unmasking a deception is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have carried out far-reaching research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been unmasked.
Lies look you in the eye.
They don't always stutter, stammer, blush, and twitch.
From this one must not conclude, however, that these liars are difficult to uncover and to expose.
A skilled lie-deacon can penetrate the truth by learning about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, the questioning and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the comprehensive and constantly growing area of unmasking, and it is clear that unmasking a deception is a modern ability that is easy to learn and helps us to cope in our complex world, especially when hiring or interviewing persons or negotiations or administration are one of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at judging other people, their interest and their own emotions, and they sense intuitively how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people lie more often than introverted people, that men are more often "self-centered" than women, whose lies are more "oriented to others" - usually to protect the feelings of others - that married people lie to their partners less frequently than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are mostly "fat lies").
We also know that when a person is exposed as a culprit, others feel less guilty of lying to that person.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First of all, by observing this person's normal behavior.
That's called baselining, the starting position.
It provides a reference point for the later assessment of changes.
Watch the posture, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
You should know better when someone usually gets his foot kicked all the time, so they don't blame him unjustly when he hits his foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of striking verbal and non-verbal behaviors.
Consider these accumulations as alarm bells that shine, not as evidence of unmasking.
People who deceive may freeze when they try to remember their story. Maybe their feet point towards the door or they lean towards the exit, change their position in a significant way or show a "relaxation after the interview," this deep, relaxing exhalation and the change in attitude when all the hard questions are over.
Questioners often falsely signal that a job interview is over just to look for this relaxation after the job interview.
Also pay attention to the language of your subject.
Scott Peterson's slipper is famous when he used the past form when he claimed that his wife was still alive and started a national search for her.
Deceptive persons can also use a distancing language: "I had no sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if you repeat a tricky question in the whole.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when answering a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth... as far as I know... to the best of my knowledge and conscience."
This makes the answer more perceptive than objective, which often causes the alarm bells to shine.
There is no magic device to unmask lies, but you can learn skills that make it possible to unmask them.
Thanks to these skills, anyone can become less likely to be the victim of fraud, both in private and professional life.
