Climatic adversities slowed the economy
In the first year in which Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and undeclared work increased in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who calls himself the initiator of change and fosters great hopes for economic growth, is in the government. However, as a result of the climatic difficulties, growth cannot be talked about, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses of millions in agriculture, but also placed tight limits on the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter.This is mainly due to the historic decline in agricultural development of 31.16 percent, which had a brake on further economic sectors.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development), 582 000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, of which 78.03 percent were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity up to November has led to a steady rise in unemployment in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid rise in unemployment in the first quarter, as between January and March 55 053 inhabitants of Sinaloa had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6.19 percent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed in Sinaloa, which is 18 969 people more than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa that year is due to several factors. Economics scholar Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments that the politics of public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently seeing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, with liquidity losses in the market as a result of the cuts in funds from legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who are forbidden to accumulate dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use them for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has fallen, due on the one hand to the problems of entry and, on the other hand, because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here and are looking for work, which increases unemployment," he says.
Unfinished business
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious, taking into account the high proportion of undeclared work, which, according to INEGI, includes 60.38 percent of workers in the country who work without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared work are the lowest wages in all of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Office for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos by September, much less than the general government average of 7375 pesos.
Decrease in FDI
In addition to reducing economic activity and increasing unemployment, the largest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI was $630,597, representing a decline of 87,74 percent compared to the $5,143,212 in the same period in the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Agency for Economic Development) for its part, recorded a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
In view of the economic crisis, the state government requested a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos at the National Congress in July to reactivate the economy in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities. The State Congress approved an amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but no positive impact of the debt on any of the economic sectors in the country could be detected by November.
Reactions
The first year of Mario López Valdé's government made it apparent to the representatives of the business community.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Manufacturing Industry in Mexico), argued that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the state government.
"Economic activity in Sinaloa was really very poor this year. It needs to be worked hard to regain the terrain lost this year and in 2012 we have to work twice. The efforts of all and in particular the progress of the already well-coordinated government team have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as frost at the beginning of the year made the country's economic development more difficult and slower.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frost. One of the most important impacts is a slowed economy that is not sufficiently moving to create an economic dynamic that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will close the year well below our expectations," he said.
Re-define vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexico Business Association) in Sinaloa, said that the government had to be encouraged to do more dynamic productive work.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the country's economic vocation and lineage, because it is important to activate all Sinaloa's material and human resources," he said.
There's a lot to do
The Chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that will guide the government's efforts in a better direction.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas, and economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas in which we can say that the government has acted more broadly. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
