The Court approves the transition to digital television in Mexico for 2015
The conversion of analogue signals to digital signals has been one of the most important changes worldwide in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional lawsuits filed by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the presidential decree, and by virtue of which the switching of analogue signals to digital signals from 2021 to 2015 must be brought forward, due to the lack of eight votes required to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, felt that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his responsibilities when he published the Legislative Decree detailing the switching to terrestrial digital television.
This decision rejected the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate, since it did not receive the required qualified majority of eight votes so that the court could decide on constitutionality or non-constitutionality. Thus, the law remains in force.
The project for the lawsuit prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero proposed that the Decree-Law be declared unconstitutional, since the regulations relating to radio and television are the responsibility of the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico), which is why the Decree-Law would contradict the hierarchical principles and the legal provisions.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the Legislative Decree. Following the adoption of the lawsuits, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the Legislative Decree and stopped all activities to set up the digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the action brought by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the debate on the project, for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the project's arguments, in the sense that the country government should not regulate the measures to be taken by the public administration with general rules.
"I also do not believe that, if we were to do so, the independence of the regulatory body would be affected." She also recalled that, for constitutional reasons, the central government is responsible for the planning of strategic policies, such as the telecommunications sector, which is responsible for government affairs.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes that have taken place around the world in recent years, and it results in better use of the radioelectric spectrum, an increased quality of the signal and more channels.
The postponement of the changeover, she said, was a postponement of the use of digitalisation, which was a decision in the public interest, which had not only technical aspects, "because it embraces economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "required the action of the entire system, according to the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a group of features that put the Constitution in the hands of the central government."
She recalled that many countries around the world had already made the digital changeover, through the government, although they had highly specialised facilities.
It could not be concluded that the government intervened in the powers of Congress by issuing the contested decree, because the laws adopted by the legislature would be respected," she assured.
The possibility to count the ballots in Michoacán individually is considered
According to PREP, the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is just under 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
The possibility of counting the ballots is a reality this year in the elections in Michoacán, because according to the data provided by the Programa de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the governor's elections is just under 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
To this end, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last November, on 9 November, the electoral office had adopted a series of rules to harmonise local rules with federal reforms in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had not adapted his political constitution, electoral law or electoral justice law to the reforms adopted by Congress, so that they had not entered into force during this round of elections. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the State Scoreboard within the time limits provided for this with the argument that he had no objection.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional action brought by the local legislature and assessed the voice of the State Commissioner on constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal," since he did not have the right to "decide or veto."
During an interview with María de los Ángeles Llanderal on the possibility of individual counting of votes, María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, there is now the possibility that the local electoral authority could partially or completely count out the ballots.
Thus, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted The results in the minutes do not agree; the minutes on the counting and calculation of votes are not available in the file or are not in the possession of the chairman of the electoral committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
In addition, the total number of complete ballots may be counted if there is a difference between the alleged winner and the one in second place, which is equal to or less than one percent, provided that there is an explicit request from the party or coalition leader, who is the second of the candidates mentioned at the beginning of the meeting.
The total number of votes may also be counted if, after completion of the ordinary calculation, it is established that the difference between the alleged winner and the candidate in second place is equal or less than one percent, provided that an explicit request is made by a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the electoral packages suspended from partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between first and second place is just under 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral records have not yet been counted.
