Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always gone to Costa Rica and Nicaragua for surfing. Together with Mexico, these are excellent places to surf. In this way, we have learned about people who love surfing.
With a view of the tour you have offered huge shows with many songs.
What plans do you have for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played there before, we don't set any limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why?
I think that's partly because we have nine records and can play over 120 songs. Everyone likes a different song, so the decision we're going to play is not easy.
If we record two or three songs that we haven't played in the repertoire for a long time, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs. Otherwise, they might get forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and I think, therefore, also for the audience.
With this tour you celebrate your twenty-year history.
When you look back, is it hard for you to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I don't think any of us imagined playing in a great rock band for more than 20 years. It looks like a dream.
We also continue to rely on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are excited about producing music.
We are lucky to be able to go to the places in the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be better.
What did it mean for you to have actively participated in the birth of Grunge?
It has always been an honor to belong to this group of big bands.
We are good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and quite unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
Sometimes a band comes out of a city, but it's unusual when five or ten groups come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We are still looking forward to being friends with them all and it honors us to be part of this upcoming Seattle sound.
It is also very unusual that a band like yours stayed together with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago. That alone is much more time than many bands survive.
First of all, I believe that we are all happy to be still alive and, moreover, we take care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up, which give every individual the freedom to experiment.
One trusts the other and his music. We couldn't get any better.
Your relationship to fame has not always been easy. On the other hand, thanks to your success, you could always do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we've grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too often, because it is too easy to fall into this game with huge crowds who love your music.
As long as you think that people have come for the music, it reminds you that you have to watch the music and what it has brought into being, without being obsessed with being a famous rock star.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and at the beginning it was great.
We were a band for three years that had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We are still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who built up the band with us. When I listen to a song or see photos, I think about what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh together and talk about music and soccer and many other topics.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The local band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their works, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why they chose the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos from several groups and we liked this band the best. That's why we're curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live.
Why do you always change Yellow Ledbetter's lyrics when you play live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing he thinks of.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
From so many+
The first to come up with me are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it is no longer a fad?
I think we all do not feel very connected to the word Grunge.
When I think about it, I think of the bands I mentioned before, for example Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others who came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think that's great, because it's worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney are making better music than ever before.
At first her music was darker, now it's more positive.
Why?
That's interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a bit frivolous, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they have something positive in themselves.
The tears came to me both when I heard Ed play them. They are very dark songs.
I think when you get older and something traumatic happened in your life - for example, when you lose a family member or a friend - it affects your artistic work and your music and these two songs clearly represent that for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
