The secretary, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, gives details of the plane accident in which the government secretary, Francisco Blake, and another seven people were killed.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Mexico Communications and Transport Secretariat) informed that the results of the investigation of the accident in which the government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and another seven people were killed indicate that the helicopter, with its whole intact structure, was hit directly against the ground without the pilot being able to launch an emergency landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary for Communications and Transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before take-off that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wings had contact with trees at 25 metres altitude, with the helicopter losing its hull, seems to indicate that the helicopter had had several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 inmates, so he fulfilled all the requirements for the transport of the personnel.
He also said that no helicopter parts were found in the field where the machine had come down.
"When searching, no aircraft parts were found elsewhere, the impact affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it fulfilled all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has a bevelling of 7 to 30 degrees.
At present, it is a priority to obtain the results of the investigation as soon as possible, but this could take several months, perhaps even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Mexico Secretariat for Aircraft and Assistance), assured that the helicopter had flown from the Estado Mayor Presidencial at cruising speed and that the aircraft had fallen on a soft slope.
"This information strengthens the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of impact."
During a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points which should be taken into account during the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of visual flight. This means that the crew would have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at the take-off. During the continuing flight towards the border area between Mexico City and the Mexico State, some low-hanging clouds arose.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that because of the clouds the crew had chosen a lower area with better visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Impact point:
The impact coordinates and the last radar recording of the helicopter are consistent. There may have been no loss of control over the aircraft or any deviation from the flight route prior to impact.
Disperse the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available to date indicates that the helicopter was bumped from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of the scattered aircraft remains suggests that the helicopter was bumped to the ground with its intact structure.
No signs of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft offer at the scene of the accident do not indicate fire or explosion.
The latest results indicate several soil contacts.
During the on-site investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9200 feet above sea level. The terrain is sloping and has a bevelling of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably broke.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had several ground contacts.
After a meticulous search in an area that went beyond the restricted area at the scene of the accident, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, which reinforces the assumption that the unbroken aircraft structure had bumped against the ground.
MSS Announces Research Protocol to Find the Gene for Obesity
She heads a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Mexico Social Insurance Institute) announced that it is conducting a research project on the discovery of the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and youth," with which the genetic markers associated with obesity are to be found.
Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was set up.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the IMSS sports grounds in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and young people are conducted every Saturday from 8.00 am.
He stressed that the investigation began on the Cuauhtémoc sports field (in the west of the state of México) and continued on the Nezahualcóyolt sports field (in the east of the state of México) since October 8th.
When the target of 500 to 600 subjects is reached, the study is continued on the sports field of Independencia (in the south of the capital district) and completed on the one of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to learn about the factors and the role of genetics in connection with the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors of Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the World Day of Diabetes, he stated that it was intended that three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 years should fill out nutrition-related questionnaires with the consent and under the supervision of their parents.
They are also asked questions about their physical activity and family history in order to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He also stated that on those Saturdays the subjects were measured (weight, size, waist circumference), their blood pressure was checked and blood values were determined such as glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (attempt to identify genes related to childhood obesity).
Cruz López stressed that this study would be carried out on the basis of the concern of health personnel about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years the proportion of obese boys has increased by 77 percent and that of obese girls by 47 percent. Overweight has also increased dramatically," emphasized the specialist at IMSS.
He claimed that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of Mexico's population differed from that of other peoples.
He stated that an average of 65 percent of Mexicans is Indian-American, 30 percent European and 5 percent African descent, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the excess of the energy (calories) that has been taken to us, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the investigators would be a comprehensive examination of the children, which would determine whether they had a degree of obesity or obesity.
It would even investigate the incidence of dark skin folds in the neck and the inner arm (acanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and pre-stage diabetes.
All information would be treated confidentially and communicated to parents in writing by the doctors. Doctors will explain all measurement results to parents and propose changes to the lifestyle that are appropriate for the prevention of diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three basic factors that are responsible for obesity, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, i.e. lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV and using transport instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, i.e. an increased consumption of sugared drinks and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with a high fat and protein intake as well as the genetics to be analyzed in this research project.
Asphalt from UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, Researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University UNAM, develops modified asphalt with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs emanating from the road surface were to be taken into account, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 potholes if the rainy season in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (City Area of the Valley of Mexico) erupted, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warning and reassuring that if laying out and maintaining the asphalt surface were to be adequately done, the number of potholes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Technically-looking punchholes," which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, which however has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid the occurrence of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound of which one part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphaltene - and the other part a low - the so-called malthene. Together, they lend the road surface its characteristic tough elastic behavior.
Toughly elastic behaviour of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very viscous and at 50°C it is almost firm, while at very low temperatures it becomes brittle.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," said the chemical engineer.
The researcher at the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of flexible road surfaces, composed of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer of asphalt consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer was bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he explained, "a final layer is laid out, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which has also been bathed in asphalt.
Since these layers are in contact with the vehicle tyres, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they must produce friction.
Those who receive and distribute most of the forces of this road surface also require an appropriate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are further important factors to consider, especially the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain gets wet, water penetrates into the layer and is only difficult to recover, causing a softening of all layers of the road surface and consequently the occurrence of potholes.
When a pothole is formed," he said, "the top layer is removed first, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards. However, the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that would have to be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (Mexico's National Research System) explained that the vehicle load was another important cause of the occurrence of potholes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be proportional to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which were already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be repaired easily and without applying high temperatures.
