So was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lophoscopist from Cali entered history when the man who identified "Alfonso Cano."
The work of these officials plays a key role.
Last November, a Lophoscopist from the CTI (Cali Procuratorate) investigation unit, who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia - Colombia's Revolutionary Armed Forces), arrived: "Alfonso Cano" by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists in the CTI department, Eliazar González was on duty this week, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career González worked in communities of Chocó, where he often had to go to the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies he was supposed to identify were located.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and after completing the necessary courses he specialised in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin, which is exposed to friction, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
In the week of deployment against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
Friday night he flew in a helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he should identify two bodies, and that there was a suspicion that one of the men who had run the oldest guerrilla in the world could be one. Therefore, he should take the ten-finger print sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his actual name).
However, when he reached the place where the body was located with the most examination, he could not identify him because of his physical appearance, because this did not resemble the images he had seen in the mass media at all.
He had no beard, was dressed like a farmer in the area, had no glasses and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a planter's cell and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the body's fingerprints to those on the print sheet.
He had seen correctly: It was "Alfonso Cano."
That same night, this man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for telling the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that it was actually the head of the FARC.
Searching for traces
For a Daktyloscope from Sijín in Cali, the appreciation given by President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the use against "Cano" was very important.
Many people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science without error rate, which can be a key factor in resolving a crime.
Lophoscopists not only identify bodies, they also support investigations into murder and robbery and confirm the identity of the arrested persons.
When they are arrested, many of the offenders present false identification documents or they have none.
We'll take their fingerprints and search them in the database.
The researcher told us that when he was stealing, he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house, because the thief had supported himself with his hand at this point when he pulled out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"Wands are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprinting, but in this case we were able to take the print of the whole hand and identify the offender who participated in several thefts," he recalled.
The fingerprints can also relieve or burden suspects of murder.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by liquor bottles.
The investigation suspected that a family member might be a suspect, and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle was consistent.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the murderer, it is linked to the place where the crime was committed.
A CTI dactyloscopicist explained that "the fingerprints with chemical or physical reagent are taken from the object."
When they appear, a planter or ribbon is used for taking away.
After that, the prints are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the civil registry.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without ID papers," said the CTI expert.
He said that not everything was the same as it was shown in the TV series SCI.
Just as not all the gold that shines is not all you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make a corresponding comparison.
