Energy policy:
Facts should prevail over dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, this is certainly energy policy.
The availability and costs of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It is reasonable to take an election meeting as an opportunity to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores the full range of economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is pushing ahead with a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, so that an enormous proportion of the world's population does not have to give up a vital element.
At the same time, it is necessary to mitigate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to combat climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany continues to live isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which submits its decision to the need to find a substitute source, nor in Switzerland, which is just planning to build only last generation nuclear power plants.
Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name just a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, decided to annex another unit to its park after Fukushima by re-establishing the Three Mile Island plant after the nuclear accident.
Although the German model, which focuses on renewable energy sources, is occasionally presented as a model, reality contradicts discourse.
The election in Berlin will take the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence, especially on Russia, due to the increased use of imported gas, an increase in CO2 emissions caused by gas and coal-fired power plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives cause for thought.
Denmark, on the one hand, is the European leader in wind energy, from which it draws 30% of its electricity, on the other hand, is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, used alternately with wind energy, and, on the other hand, its CO2 emissions and electricity prices are 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the stability of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than our French households.
Since the energy price in the globalised economy is a key factor in competitiveness and a stability stake for industry on national soil, French companies have an advantage because of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore lead to a strong increase in energy prices, which made the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys showed that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are just as unwilling to pay, as it shows resistance to the principle of this source of energy.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125.00 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a large number of specialized small and medium-sized enterprises to the international markets and makes them the creators of countless jobs.
Should France decide to withdraw from nuclear power, a large part of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the annual 6 billion euros of capital goods and nuclear energy exports would shrink more and more.
What electrician would hire an EPR designed to work for sixty years if the decline of his producer was pre-programmed?
In order to solve the energetic equation, one must admit that there is just as little a work of devils as there is a miracle means of generating electricity.
The low-carbon solutions for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy developed by Areva demonstrate the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a safety authority which carries out uncompromising and transparent controls at existing plants, such as at the construction site in Flamanville.
Their work teams, who have made a name for themselves because of their professionalism, are now obsessed with the idea of security.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, namely in Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions, so it ran without consequences for man and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was provoked by reactor construction and inexcusable human failure.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented proportions that caused the death of several tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn the same lessons from this accident as it did after the previous two.
As a result of this approach, as well as cooperation between the safety authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR is a draft that allows it to resist such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among the electrical engineers to build a nuclear power plant, a stop to construction in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF by allowing them to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is imperative and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party leaders dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy led by Nicolas Sarkozy was criticized from many angles - overloading police, judicial and administrative bodies on the basis of a policy subject to the numbers, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights," as France had called itself.
Recently, the harassment directed against foreign students from the authorities had shaped the weekly shows, the Minister of the Interior had casually announced (see Libération of 23 May) that France "has no need for talents, masons or waiters from abroad."
But this policy was rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
On the right, Jacques Chirac, who had declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed people, including more than 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for one country," was quoted on the left by Michel Rocard, who had stated in 1990 that France "could not absorb the entire poverty of the world."
The only difference is the degree of generosity
The fear of the invasion of the national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was divided in 2005 from both the right and the left.
From both camps the immigrants were perceived as a burden for the economy and the French society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity one is willing to admit to immigrants.
In his programme, Francois Hollande confines himself to banalities that point to partnership development allowing our "migration problems" to be solved.
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on the elections; however, it is economically costly.
As economic experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron remind us in a recent work that summarizes the latest insights into immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of the flood of immigrants on economic growth, wages and jobs in immigration countries.
Limiting immigration would reduce growth and damage the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to substitute the domestic labour force, in particular the less skilled, by exerting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are, in fact, much more complementary than domestic wage-earners, since they are mainly engaged in occupations in sectors that are untroubled in terms of employment.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local wage-earners, the more skilled among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not aligned with the labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would find it difficult to work in a country where there is a lack of anesthetists, so this complementarity also results in a positive effect of immigration on wages and the domestic labour market situation between locals and migrants.
Giovanni Peri calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants resulted in an included, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this, without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas created by immigrants is beneficial to economic growth (high proportion of naturalised immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to welfare systems, in the European countries on average about 1% of the total budget.
For example, the World Labour Organization estimates that an immigrant at the age of 30 to Germany will, on average, contribute a net contribution (revenue minus expenditure) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wished to achieve the missing intersections "with his teeth" at the beginning of his mandate.
However, these said teeth, which were to deter immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, now remains to think through European democracy
Democracy is a valuable asset; it is also a sensitive asset.
