"Contactless" chip cards become common goods
The world fair for chip cards opens its doors on Tuesday in Villepinte near Paris in an optimistic attitude.
According to Eurosmart, 2011 should end with an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor chips (EC cards, SIM card phone), with more than 6 billion units sold.
The most important segment is contactless technology, which allows payments in public transport or payment of purchases by simply holding the card to a reader.
Compared to the 320 million sold a year earlier, 460 million contactless chip cards were to be sold worldwide this year!
Their market share should increase even further in 2012 (580 million units expected) and represent more than 10% of the global chip card market (6,925 million cards).
Europe is gaining ground in terms of contactless payment, after it has long lags behind the Asia-Pacific region.
Some 26 million Visa cards are already equipped with this functionality, and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are rather modest: only 400,000 contactless visa cards have been distributed.
However, the consumer markets are making steam.
Carrefour has therefore issued 2.5 million contactless pass MasterCards this year.
In order to move to higher speed, it is now necessary for banks to equip their customers with these cards.
"Two large French financial institutions have committed themselves to systematically handing out bank cards to their customers in the future, which are equipped with contactless chip," announces Gérard Nébouy, Director General of Visa Europe France.
Banks test payment by cell phone
However, this is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
A negligible percentage of devices have been equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology necessary to carry out these transactions.
"They have fallen behind."
"But they should experience a real upward trend at least next year."
"We expect sales of 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012," explains Marc Bertin, President of Eurosmart.
But the banks are taking an initiative.
The Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the launch of a test run in Caen, which will run from December to next June.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees are to be equipped with a capsule that allows contactless payment.
BPCE is running a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société Générale had also declared yesterday to prepare for the launch of an offer that allows their customers contactless payment by cell phone.
Terrorist front understands itself, from the Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about the relations between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The long suspected relations between the terrorist group al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram seem to be confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel himself confirmed that Algiers had now "achieved certainty."
"The way in which both organizations operate and the relations of the intelligence services point to clear cooperation," he explained without going further into detail.
Paris seems to be doing a similar analysis.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January has revealed interfaces.
The Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by followers of the Aqmi are said to have been killed the following day at the same time as several of their kidnappers on the occasion of an operation carried out by the French special forces.
French and Nigerian investigators want to have found several phone chips in the debris at the site that belonged to the terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The analysis of telephone calls leads to several interlocutors stationed in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), the investigators are particularly interested in the numbers of two interlocutors: one number leads to a Nigerian who for a long time had stayed in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram; the other leads to a man who is considered to be close to the Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but there is no doubt that we need to wait for more clear evidence before we can talk about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Harem."
"It's conceivable, though."
"It has been known for years that the sect has received financial and intellectual support from outside and that it is increasingly active," the Nigerian researcher Kunle Amuwo softens.
In recent months, these "support services' have become more and more obvious in their course, as well as Boko Harem's speeches and operating modes, which now indicate the addition of suicide bombers and the use of ever more complex explosives bearing the same handwriting as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, to begin with Washington, has since then put pressure on Abuja to take account of the problems caused by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities have in fact for a long time regarded the grouping as a community of Illuminati, which should not be given special attention.
Rapid success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri near a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist Iman Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram - which means "Western education is a disgrace" in Haoussa - is pursuing the establishment of an Islamic Emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this destitute region, the merger is very successful.
It politicizes itself and demands strict observance of Sharia, while the activists associated with it fight against the ungodly central government.
The activists initially target churches, bars and authorities.
In 2009, Boko Haram's activists were particularly active in their intensified attacks against the Commissariat.
However, Abuja's reaction is indifferent as usual.
The army surrounds the city, and 800 people are killed.
Mohammed Yusuf, imprisoned, is killed in prison.
As a result, the sect is becoming increasingly radical and leaving its strongholds in the north.
Last Christmas she confessed to an assassination attempt in Jos, which claimed 80 lives, and then another one in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram will be blamed for a suicide attack that took place in the secure police headquarters in Abuja - the first of its kind.
In August, the United Nations' local headquarters became the primary international target.
The formation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which is to lead from Mauritania to Nigeria to Somalia, has been worrying all security experts ever since.
While the Aqmi occupied Mali and Niger operating Somalis from al-Shabaab in Kenya, Boko Harem seems to be a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, on the occasion of a discussion with President Goodluck Jonathan in Nigeria, Alain Juppé warned against Boko Harem and showed his willingness to "tell all the clues."
