Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the bottom of the Baltic Sea and connects western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is intended to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with splendour and glory.
Over 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly under sea level last Tuesday under orchestral sound and at the gourmet buffet.
German chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have symbolically jointly turned the valve's steering system, which transports the Russian gas into the West European network.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year will be delivered to Western Europe by a first pipeline of 1,224 km in length connecting the Saint Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - the equivalent of total French consumption - will be completed by the end of 2012.
And one already lets the eventuality of the construction of a third line sound on its own track.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous building looks like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
Indeed, the Nord-Stream pipeline will allow direct gas delivery to Germany, avoiding any route route by third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing some of their power: it is now becoming more difficult for them to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most engaged in the debate, did not hesitate to compare the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-Asian pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically very sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of defusing European energy, as the project has broken the gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In barely five years Russia has managed to achieve its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which have strong gas consumption and whose gas reserves are running out.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," confirmed François Fillon at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out the extent to which the large gas contracts are also important from the political and economic side.
All this explains the broad smile of the numerous Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with concrete sheathing, which it is intended to protect from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, about 200 m deep.
During their construction, minefields dated from the Second World War had to be avoided.
"Hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, Spokesman of Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect fauna and flora.
The cable is a long line of metal, heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted by anything over the entire length: neither by valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the Swedish coast, but the project managers have refrained from it, as the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state company permanently located at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas outlet in less than a minute," Jens Müller specified.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered to be unlikely by the designers, as the weld seams were estimated to have a leak per 100,000 years.
The state monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled from a seaship for external observation purposes and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, a diameter of one metre, is introduced into the inside of the pipeline and moved through the gas pressure.
After three complete days of movement through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides on arrival the most accurate information about any deformations of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to function for fifty years without even having to undergo the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is easily guaranteed by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entry point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have united their forces to realize this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated (each 15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (each 9%).
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company on a renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the quantity of gas transported is," Jens Müller specified.
The financing of gas pipeline construction was secured by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
Total labour costs should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the total investment amounted to 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are certain to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The gas pipeline appears on a sandy, pine-forested stretch of coast near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5 metre high valves form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other indicators of the incoming gas before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per hour.
With full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give the letter a new style.
It has a flair of adventure, hours spent writing by candlelight.
The notebook of Moleskine is easily recognizable again, with its black, rectangular cover, its elastic band, the egg-scarf sides, aged over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, which is based in Milan, decided to launch a distinguished design notebook on the market at the time.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, is responsible for the market launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by a traditional production technique called Mole Skin, which refers to a cotton bag used for covering upholstery benches, for example.
This kind of notebook was very popular among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object, which until the 20th century was regarded as an icon of avant-garde artists," explains Maria Sebregondi, now head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success comes in.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and were established with a sales volume of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to make a phantom picture of the buyers, as the notebook inspires businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultivated and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its beginnings, now employs more than 100 people and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
The company sells its notebooks in bookshops, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques of the city centers and understands how to enforce its identity.
"We have followed the Zeitgeist and its new writing needs, which exist despite the upswing of the e-mails," explained Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the company Moleskine: Recently, the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour" in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a cover with leopard patterns at the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine profited from its success and cultural zeitgeist and managed to diversify its products: bags, appointment calendars, fillers, computer covers... The brand has the entire range of articles.
A success that brings envy to the plan: In the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today's Syntegra Capital, and thus opened a new chapter in the history of Moleskine.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such high levels?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today the "15th week of work for the disabled" begins.
Despite a targeted public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people is always twice as high as the average: 19% against 9% unemployment of the total population.
Disheartening?
"No, that's what Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Association Adapt, emphasizes, which hosts the "week of work for the disabled."
"The progress made within fifteen years is considerable."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not double, but three times as high."
"Nevertheless, much remains to be done."
However, it must be said that many obstacles continue to exist for disabled unemployed people before they get a job.
It is more common for older people: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them do not have a high school diploma and there are only 10,000 disabled people among the 2.3 million students with a higher level of education.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% for the total.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it more difficult to re-enter the labour market and which "make the core of the problem," says Christian Gramin, Director General of Tremplin, a association founded in 1992, which helps companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the physical brakes.
The unspoken remains, the attitudes that, although certain, are slowly evolving.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for La Cité magazine stated that the managers interviewed had "a weak level of knowledge about the disabled" that was "over-represented" by "persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually impaired."
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment target of 6% disabled workers, which was laid down in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, which date back to 2008, refer to a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now at around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, General Director of Agefiph, the organisation responsible for collecting contributions from companies that violate this law.
The proof: The number of "fees paid" establishments, as well as the sum of the paid-up amounts, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which provides for increased contributions, created a lot of pressure on the companies, Pierre Blanc explained."
"But this improvement also reflects real knowledge, especially among the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of the sites employ disabled workers between 20 and 49 employees, while companies with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
